{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523534"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13905"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13905"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.03,0.02,0.61,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6524"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102098"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6524"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2024-07-08T21:31:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-31T15:53:12+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-07-12T07:12:52+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-24 13:49:02"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13905"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84543"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13032"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46100"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84543"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102098"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-week history of altered bowel habits. He describes increasing constipation and difficulty passing stools. He reports feeling that he has not been able to completely empty his bowels lately and has noticed his stools have become narrower. He has lost about 5 kg of weight over the last two months despite no change in his appetite. He has a history of diverticulosis diagnosed five years ago but no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is soft and non-tender. Digital rectal examination reveals no masses. He has already undergone a CT scan of the abdomen. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation to establish the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flexible sigmoidoscopy with biopsy","Virtual colonoscopy with contrast","Faecal immunochemical test","Colonoscopy","Contrast-enhanced MRI rectum"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan showed a mass at the rectosigmoid junction highly suspicious for a carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis in this case. It is the gold standard for diagnosing colorectal cancer, which is the primary concern given the patient\u0027s age and symptoms. Colonoscopy allows direct visualisation of the entire colon and rectum, and enables the physician to take biopsies of any suspicious lesions for definitive diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexible sigmoidoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E with biopsy would visualize the rectum and sigmoid colon and could potentially identify the lesion seen on CT at the rectosigmoid junction. However, it is limited in its reach (examining only up to 60 cm from the anal verge) and would not evaluate the entire colon. Given the high prevalence of synchronous lesions in colorectal cancer (approximately 5%), a complete colonoscopy is preferred to ensure no additional lesions are missed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVirtual colonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E with contrast (CT colonography) is a reasonable alternative for patients who cannot undergo conventional colonoscopy. However, it has limitations including inability to take biopsies, lower sensitivity for small or flat lesions, and the need for subsequent colonoscopy if abnormalities are detected. Given that a suspicious lesion has already been identified on CT, proceeding directly to conventional colonoscopy would be more efficient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal immunochemical test\u003C/strong\u003E is used primarily as a screening tool for colorectal cancer. While this test may be positive in this patient, it would not provide a definitive diagnosis and would unnecessarily delay appropriate management. When there is already a high suspicion of colorectal cancer based on symptoms and imaging, proceeding directly to a diagnostic test that can provide tissue confirmation is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContrast-enhanced MRI rectum\u003C/strong\u003E is an excellent modality for local staging of rectal cancer once diagnosed, particularly for assessing the relationship of the tumour to the mesorectal fascia and determining the need for neoadjuvant therapy. However, it is not the most appropriate initial diagnostic test for suspected colorectal cancer as it cannot provide histological confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms of altered bowel habits, constipation, change in stool caliber, and significant weight loss in an older adult are red flags for colorectal cancer. These symptoms warrant a full colonoscopy for proper evaluation and diagnosis. Colonoscopy not only allows for direct visualisation of any lesions but also enables immediate biopsy for histological confirmation of the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colonoscopy is the gold standard investigation for diagnosing colorectal cancer in patients presenting with altered bowel habits and suspicious symptoms.","Weight loss, change in bowel habits, and constipation in older adults are red flag symptoms for colorectal cancer.","Colonoscopy allows for direct visualization of the colon and rectum, as well as biopsy of suspicious lesions for definitive diagnosis."],"references":["Menon G, Recio-Boiles A, Lotfollahzadeh S, et al. Colon Cancer. [Updated 2024 Apr 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470380/","Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Bowel cancer: a guide for GP. Aust Fam Physician. 2006 Apr;35(4):192\u20134. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/34321aa9-9abc-4ff2-9c2b-f382332df893/attachment.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84543"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13905"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20840"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20840"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/g89NcQzR0M3cjS5tOHFFs7pBxtruPe.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/g89NcQzR0M3cjS5tOHFFs7pBxtruPe.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":793,"height":631}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84543"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-07T16: